in general you want to avoid type(foo) == concrete_type and instead use isinstance, e.g. isinstance(classifiers, list).  of course, there are other iterable things that are not lists, so to be fully compatible, you might want something like:

``` python
def maybe_list(value, expected_type=str):
  from collections import Iterable
  if isinstance(value, expected_type):
    return [value]
  elif isinstance(value, Iterable):
    real_values = list(iter(value))
    if not all(isinstance(v, expected_type) for v in real_values):
      raise ValueError('Element of list is not of type %r' % expected_type)
    return real_values
  else:
    raise ValueError('Value must be a %r or iterable of %r' % (expected_type, expected_type))
```

then in several places in twitter-commons, we should just be doing, e.g.

self.classifiers = maybe_list(classifiers)

